nda]] in [[Taskmaster]]'s Academy,{{issue|date=December 2012}} but Diamondback had subsequently dishonored Snapdragon in some form.{{issue|date=December 2012}}  While on the S.S. ''Superia'' cruise ship, Snapdragon apprehended Diamondback and threw her off, leaving her to drown.{{issue|date=December 2012}}  Diamondback eventually recovered and received the super-soldier serum in one of her misadventures, and during their rematch, choked Snapdragon to death.{{issue|date=December 2012}}  Her body was returned to Japan and cremated by her brother, Kono.<ref>''Captain America'' #413</ref>\n\nLater, the name Snapdragon was taken by [[Diamondback (comics)|Rachael Leighton]] after she began working for [[Superia]] as payment for finding a cure for the glitch in the super-soldier serum.<ref>''Avengers'' #387</ref>\n\nA woman calling herself Sheoke Sanda appeared in ''Moon Knight''.<ref>''Moon Knight'' #2 2011</ref> If this is the original Snapdragon details of her resurrection are unknown.\n\n==Powers and abilities==\nSnapdragon possesses no superhuman abilities other than a protective suit and a helmet with infrared sensors. She is a master in hand-to-hand combat, and skilled with various forms of weaponry.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Marvunapp|http://www.marvunapp.com/Appendix/snapdrag.htm|Snapdragon}}\n\n[[Category:Female supervillains]]\n[[Category:Fictional assassins]]\n[[Category:Fictional martial artists]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics martial artists]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics supervillains]]\n\n\n{{Marvel-villain-stub}}"}]}}}}